<div id="review_1703280253" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1703280253" />
    <a title="James McCormick" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29877058-james-mccormick"><img alt="James McCormick" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1472371354p2/29877058.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1703280253?book_show_action=true">Jul 19, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="James McCormick" class="user" itemprop="url" name="James McCormick" href="/user/show/29877058-james-mccormick">James McCormick</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1703280253" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5270748972605353814">I don’t usually post negative reviews. If I don’t like a book, then I simply don’t write about it. Sidney Sheldon’s “Are you Afraid of the Dark?” however was such a disappointment I have to make an exception. <br/><br/>One of the biggest surprises (Sheldon was after all a playwright and a scriptwriter) was the dialogue. Stilted, flat (no-one seems to use contractions) and “on the nose” (to borrow a screenwriting term) it was at times painful to read. It was almost as if the author had written a first draf</span>
  <span id="freeText5270748972605353814" style="display:none">I don’t usually post negative reviews. If I don’t like a book, then I simply don’t write about it. Sidney Sheldon’s “Are you Afraid of the Dark?” however was such a disappointment I have to make an exception. <br /><br />One of the biggest surprises (Sheldon was after all a playwright and a scriptwriter) was the dialogue. Stilted, flat (no-one seems to use contractions) and “on the nose” (to borrow a screenwriting term) it was at times painful to read. It was almost as if the author had written a first draft of a script and not bothered to revise it. The dual female protagonists’ romantic flashbacks in particular are cringe-worthy as are their continual lamentations for their murdered true loves.<br /><br />Similarly, the villain of the piece, Tanner Kingsley, is little more than a pantomime villain, a psychopath by degrees smooth and charming then choleric and snarling. I lost count of the times he growls out orders to “kill those bitches” as his successive murder attempts fail, but it’s fairly high up in the double digits.<br /><br />The novel reads like a cartoon series of adventures, think the Hooded Claw trying to finish off Penelope Pitstop using a variety of innovative and creative methods. Every twist or surprise was also totally predictable and there was only one, near the end, that wrapped things up neatly which I didn’t see coming.<br /><br />As stated above, I don’t usually like to write bad reviews, but the late Mr Sheldon is a towering figure in modern literature with three hundred million books sold and eighteen best sellers and numerous awards to his name. I don’t think one bad review from me is going to affect his reputation too badly.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5270748972605353814" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


